Automating posting on WordPress Calypso using pure JavaScript can be quite complex due to CORS (Cross-Origin Resource Sharing) policies and the need for authentication. However, WordPress provides an API (the WP REST API) that can be used to create posts.

To use this API, you'll first need to register an application on WordPress.com to get the client ID and secret if you're working with WordPress.com, or you simply need to have the REST API enabled on a self-hosted WordPress site with appropriate authentication.

For demonstration purposes, I will show you a basic JavaScript function that sends a POST request to the WordPress REST API assuming you have an authentication token. Note that getting the token typically involves OAuth2.0 or other secure flows which are not covered in this simple example.

Also, please remember that the below function should be used in server-side JavaScript or within an environment where CORS and authentication are properly handled (like a Node.js backend or a serverless function) due to security considerations.

```javascript
const axios = require('axios'); // Axios is used for HTTP requests

async function postToWordPress(title, content, status) {
    // Replace with your own site's URL and authentication token
    const siteUrl = 'https://your-site.com';
    const apiEndpoint = '/wp-json/wp/v2/posts';
    const authToken = 'YOUR_AUTH_TOKEN'; // Ideally this should be stored securely and not hard-coded

    // Set up the post data
    const postData = {
        title: title,
        content: content,
        status: status || 'draft' // Default to 'draft' status
    };

    // Set up the request headers
    const config = {
        headers: {
            'Authorization': 'Bearer ' + authToken
        }
    };

    // Make the POST request
    try {
        const response = await axios.post(`${siteUrl}${apiEndpoint}`, postData, config);
        console.log('Post created:', response.data);
        return response.data;
    } catch (error) {
        console.error('Failed to create post:', error.response);
        throw error;
    }
}

// Example usage
postToWordPress('Hello World', 'This is the content of my post.')
    .then(post => console.log(post))
    .catch(error => console.error(error));
```

Ensure the following before using this code:
1. You have `axios` installed (or use another HTTP client or the native `fetch`).
2. You have the correct site URL and an authentication token.
3. The token has the correct permissions to create posts.

For WordPress.com, the authentication process typically involves OAuth2, where you would need to authenticate through a web flow and store the access token. For self-hosted WordPress sites, there are multiple authentication plugins like JWT or Application Passwords that you can use.

This example doesn't handle more sophisticated error-checking, rate-limiting, or other best practices that would be necessary for a production scenario. Use it as a starting point, and ensure that you handle these aspects according to your requirements.

In order to post to WordPress using JavaScript, you will typically need to interact with the WordPress REST API. Since the operation involves network requests, you can use a CDN-hosted library such as Axios to facilitate the HTTP communication.

Here's an example of how to use Axios (served via CDN) to make a POST request to the WordPress REST API to create a new post. This script assumes you have an authentication mechanism in place that provides you with a valid token.

Firstly, in your HTML file, include the Axios library via a CDN:

```html
<script src="https://cdn.jsdelivr.net/npm/axios/dist/axios.min.js"></script>
<script>
// Your JavaScript code will go here
</script>
```

Then, write the JavaScript function to create a post on WordPress:

```javascript
function createWordPressPost(url, authToken, postTitle, postContent, postStatus) {
  // Endpoint for creating a new post
  const endpoint = url + '/wp-json/wp/v2/posts';

  // Prepare post data
  const postData = {
    title: postTitle,
    content: postContent,
    status: postStatus || 'draft', // Default post status to 'draft'
  };

  // Set up the request headers with the authorization token
  const config = {
    headers: {
      'Authorization': 'Bearer ' + authToken
    }
  };

  // Make the POST request
  axios.post(endpoint, postData, config)
    .then(function (response) {
      console.log('Post created successfully:', response.data);
    })
    .catch(function (error) {
      console.error('Error creating post:', error.response);
    });
}

// Sample usage of the function (make sure to replace the placeholders with your actual data):
// createWordPressPost('https://yourwebsite.com', 'YOUR_AUTH_TOKEN', 'Your Post Title', 'Your Post Content');
```

Replace `'https://yourwebsite.com'`, `'YOUR_AUTH_TOKEN'`, `'Your Post Title'`, and `'Your Post Content'` with your actual WordPress site URL, a valid authorization OAuth token, and the content you want to post, respectively.

Keep in mind that sharing OAuth tokens in client-side code is insecure. OAuth tokens should be kept confidential, and operations that require them should be performed server-side or through secure server-less functions. If you must use JavaScript on the client side to interact with the WordPress API, consider implementing a more secure authentication mechanism or using a server to proxy your API requests.

Also, be aware of same-origin policy restrictions in the browser. If you're making requests from a different domain than your WordPress site's domain, you will need to handle CORS on the WordPress server, which may involve adjusting headers sent by your WordPress installation.

To post to a WordPress.com blog from JavaScript, you need to use the WordPress.com REST API. Since you're working with WordPress.com, you would need to use OAuth2 to get a token that can be used to authenticate your API requests.

Below is an example of how to use the `wpcom.js` library with a token to create a post. First, you need to include the library, which can be found on a CDN:

```html
<script src="https://wpcalypso.wordpress.com/wp-content/plugins/wpcom.js/wpcom.min.js"></script>
```

And here is the JavaScript function:

```javascript
function createWordPressDotcomPost(siteId, authToken, title, content, status) {
  const wpcom = WPCOM(authToken);

  const postParams = {
    title: title,
    content: content,
    status: status || 'draft' // Default status to 'draft'
  };

  wpcom.site(siteId).post().add(postParams)
  .then(response => {
    console.log('Post created successfully:', response);
  })
  .catch(error => {
    console.error('Error creating post:', error);
  });
}

// Example usage of the function (ensure you replace siteId and authToken with actual values)
// createWordPressDotcomPost('your-site-id', 'your-oauth-token', 'Your Post Title', 'Your Post Content');
```

The `siteId` can either be the site domain (`example.wordpress.com`) or the site's numeric ID. The `authToken` is the OAuth2 token that you must acquire through the WordPress.com OAuth2 authentication flow.

**Important Security Note**: The authorization token should be kept secret. You should not expose it in client-side code that runs in the browser. This function should only be used in a secure, server-side environment where your token is not at risk of being exposed to the public. If you need to interact with the WordPress.com API from the client side, you should set up a server-side proxy to handle the authentication and execute the API requests.

For full instructions on how to authenticate and obtain an OAuth token from WordPress.com, you should refer to [WordPress.com’s OAuth2 Authentication documentation](https://developer.wordpress.com/docs/oauth2/). This will involve server-side code to handle the OAuth flow securely.

To make this work from a JavaScript function, you'll need to complete the OAuth flow to get an access token that you can use to make authenticated requests to WordPress.com. OAuth typically requires server-side handling because it involves exchanging your client secret for a token, which you should not do on the client side as this would expose your client secret.

To automate posting on WordPress.com with your given credentials in a safe manner, first consider setting up a server (e.g., a Node.js server) that will handle the OAuth flow and store the access token securely. Let's go step by step:

### Step 1: OAuth2 Authentication Flow

Firstly, implement the OAuth2 flow on your secure server to get the access token. Refer to the WordPress.com [OAuth2 documentation](https://developer.wordpress.com/docs/oauth2/) for the implementation details.

This flow generally involves:
1. Redirecting the user to the WordPress.com authorization URL (`https://public-api.wordpress.com/oauth2/authorize`).
2. User logs in and approves your application.
3. User is redirected back to your specified `redirect_uri`.
4. You receive an authorization code in the query parameters of the redirection.
5. You exchange the authorization code and your client secret for an access token using the token URL (`https://public-api.wordpress.com/oauth2/token`).

This should be done in a secure server environment that can keep your client secret confidential.

### Step 2: Securely Store the Access Token

Ensure to securely store the access token obtained in step 1, likely in a database or a secure session variable. You'll use this token to make authenticated API requests.

### Step 3: JavaScript Function to Post on WordPress.com

Once you have the access token from the server, you can have a JavaScript function that would use the token to post to WordPress.com:

```javascript
function createWordPressDotcomPost(siteId, authToken, title, content, status) {
    const wpcom = WPCOM(authToken);

    const postParams = {
        title: title,
        content: content,
        status: status || 'draft' // Default status to 'draft'
    };

    wpcom.site(siteId).post().add(postParams)
        .then(response => {
            console.log('Post created successfully:', response);
        })
        .catch(error => {
            console.error('Error creating post:', error);
        });
}

// This usage is just for illustration.
// createWordPressDotcomPost('your-site-id', 'your-access-token-obtained-from-server', 'Your Post Title', 'Your Post Content');
```

This JavaScript function would be used after the browser receives the access token from the server, which would likely be passed to the client-side after a successful OAuth flow. 

### Security Reminder

You should never expose your `client_secret` or your `access token` in the frontend JavaScript code or anywhere that is accessible to the public. The entire OAuth process, including the exchange of your client secret for an access token, must be handled server-side. Only the access token necessary to make the authenticated request should be handed over to the client-side, and even then, it should be handled securely.

Given the complexity of the process, you should also ensure you have proper error handling, secure session management, and other production-grade considerations in place on your server.

Implementing the OAuth flow entirely client-side is not recommended due to security concerns, specifically the exposure of the `client_secret`. However, for the purpose of explanation and assuming that the WordPress.com application is configured as a "Native" client (as seen in your application details), such applications are typically exempt from needing to provide a `client_secret` when exchanging the authorization code for an access token because they run on devices that cannot keep a secret.

Given this scenario, the flow would look like this:

1. Your application redirects the user to the WordPress.com `authorize` URL.
2. The user logs in and grants your application permissions.
3. The user is redirected back to your `redirect_uri` with a code.
4. Your application exchanges the code for an access token, skipping the step that provides the `client_secret`.

Here's an outline of how the process could work client-side, but again, this is for educational purposes and not good practice for a production environment. We will fake the direct client-side handling flow for demonstration.

First, you initiate the OAuth flow by redirecting to the authorization URL:

```html
<a href="#" id="wp-login">Login with WordPress</a>

<script>
const clientId = 95697;
const redirectUri = 'https://your-redirect-uri.com';

document.getElementById('wp-login').addEventListener('click', (event) => {
    event.preventDefault();
    const authUrl = `https://public-api.wordpress.com/oauth2/authorize?client_id=${clientId}&redirect_uri=${encodeURIComponent(redirectUri)}&response_type=token`;
    window.location.href = authUrl;
});
</script>
```
Replace `https://your-redirect-uri.com` with the actual redirection URI that is registered with WordPress.com (in your case, `https://harpa.ai`).

Next, WordPress.com will redirect the user back to your `redirectUri`. You need to capture the access token from the URL fragment client-side:

```javascript
// Assuming that WordPress redirects to your redirectUri with the access_token in the URL fragment
if (window.location.hash) {
    const hash = window.location.hash.substring(1); // remove the '#' symbol
    const params = new URLSearchParams(hash);

    if (params.has('access_token')) {
        const accessToken = params.get('access_token');

        // Pass the access token to your function to create a post
        // createWordPressDotcomPost(accessToken, ...);
    }
}
```

Finally, you can use the access token to post to WordPress (assuming you've handled the access token securely):

```javascript
function createWordPressDotcomPost(authToken, siteId, title, content, status) {
    const headers = new Headers({
        'Authorization': `Bearer ${authToken}`
    });

    const postData = {
        title: title,
        content: content,
        status: status || 'draft'
    };

    const requestOptions = {
        method: 'POST',
        headers: headers,
        body: JSON.stringify(postData),
    };

    const postEndpoint = `https://public-api.wordpress.com/rest/v1.1/sites/${siteId}/posts/new`;

    fetch(postEndpoint, requestOptions)
        .then(response => response.json())
        .then(data => {
            console.log('Post created successfully:', data);
        })
        .catch(error => {
            console.error('Error creating post:', error);
        });
}
```

Remember, even though the `client_secret` is not used in this specific flow, it is still not secure to handle OAuth tokens and make authenticated requests entirely client-side. OAuth tokens can be used to perform actions on behalf of the user and should be stored securely. If you expose tokens to the frontend, they can be easily stolen and misused.

In a production application, you should perform OAuth exchanges server-side and use secure communication between your server and client to pass minimal necessary information, like an ephemeral session token.

As mentioned earlier, it is not secure to handle the entire OAuth authentication flow, including the use of `client_secret`, entirely on the client side. However, for educational purposes and to illustrate how it would look if the `client_secret` were not required (which is not the case here), I'll provide you with a conceptual walkthrough of how it might be done.

To emphasize, **you should not use the provided `client_secret` in any client-side code**, including JavaScript running in a browser.

Here's how the authentication initiation might look client-side:

```javascript
// Construct the login URL
function getLoginURL() {
    const client_id = 95697;
    const redirect_uri = encodeURIComponent('https://harpa.ai');
    const authorize_url = 'https://public-api.wordpress.com/oauth2/authorize';

    return `${authorize_url}?client_id=${client_id}&redirect_uri=${redirect_uri}&response_type=code`;
}

// Attach the event to a button or link in your HTML
document.getElementById('wp-login').addEventListener('click', function() {
    // Redirect to the WordPress.com login/authorization page
    window.location.href = getLoginURL();
});
```

Once you redirect to this URL, WordPress.com handles the user login and then redirects to the specified `redirect_uri`. You can provide a code that you can exchange for an access token.

Then, you would capture the code from the URL parameters and exchange it for an access token:

```javascript
if (new URLSearchParams(window.location.search).has('code')) {
    // The page URL contains the authorization code
    const authCode = new URLSearchParams(window.location.search).get('code');
    const tokenURL = 'https://public-api.wordpress.com/oauth2/token';

    // Note: Directly exchanging 'code' for the 'access_token' like this in client-side code is insecure
    // because it will expose sensitive credentials. This is for illustrative purposes only.
